photo.description: Leaf [4]v (p. [8]) of 4 unnumbered ms. leaves in the hand of Johannes Cuno (1463-1513) containing the Greek text and a Latin translation of the Golden Verses (attributed to Pythagoras) copied on 10 August 1496 in Stuttgart from a book owned by Johann Reuchlin (1455-1522) and bound in at the end of Cuno's copy of Giovanni Arispa's Latin translation of Hierocles's Commentarius in aurea Pythagoreorum carmina (Padua: Bartholomaeus de Valdezoccho, 17 Apr. 1474). Cf. colophon. According to M. Sicherl, the text and translation are copied from an edition (ISTC il00068000) of the Golden Verses printed (with the Erotemata of Constantine Lascaris and several other works) by Aldus Manutius in Venice on 28 Feb. 1494/95 and 8 Mar. 1495 (Johannes Cuno ... Eine biographisch-kodikologische Studie (Heidelberg: Winter, 1978), p. 209). Established heading: Cuno, Johannes, 1463-1513 Established heading: Reuchlin, Johann, 1455-1522 Established heading: Golden verses Penn Libraries call number: Inc H-151 All images from this book
photo.title: Leaf [4]v (p. [8]) of 4 unnumbered ms. leaves in the hand of Johannes Cuno (1463-1513) containing the Greek text and a Latin translation of the Golden Verses copied on 10 August 1496 in Stuttgart from a book owned by Johann Reuchlin (1455-1522)

photo.description: Finis aureo[rum] Carminu[m] Pythagore s[cri]pta veloci[ssi]me i[n] Stuttg[art] accom[o]da[n]te d[omi]no doctore Reuchlin Grece [overwritten: hebraice] lingue sui t[empo]ris ap[u]d G[er]manos [per]iti[ssi]mo 1496 Laur[en]cij. Colophon on leaf [4]r (p. [7]) of 4 unnumbered ms. leaves in the hand of Johannes Cuno (1463-1513) containing the Greek text and a Latin translation of the Golden Verses (attributed to Pythagoras) copied on 10 August 1496 in Stuttgart from a book owned by Johann Reuchlin (1455-1522) and bound in at the end of Cuno's copy of Giovanni Arispa's Latin translation of Hierocles's Commentarius in aurea Pythagoreorum carmina (Padua: Bartholomaeus de Valdezoccho, 17 Apr. 1474). The bookseller's description translates: End of the Golden Verses of Pythagoras, written in a great hurry at Stuttgart (from a copy) lent by Dr. Reuchlin, the most expert in his day in the Greek [overwritten: Hebrew] language among all Germans. 1496 on St. Laurence's day. For the correction of "Hebraice" to "Grece," see M. Sicherl, Johannes Cuno ... Eine biographisch-kodikologische Studie (Heidelberg: Winter, 1978), p. 208. According to M. photo.description: Printer's device of Nicolaus Episcopius the younger of Basel (here used by his heirs and brother Eusebius), featuring "a crane, a symbol of continual watchfulness and sharp discernment, and holds a stone in one of its claws so as not to fall asleep. The hand extending from a cloud grasps a bishop's crozier on which the crane is perched. Written across the top of the staff is EPISCOP, which is the shortened form of the Latin word for bishop 'Episcopus,' but also is a wordplay on the name of the printer."--Pitts Theology Library Digital Image Archive. Established heading: Episcopius, Nicolaus, 1531-1565 Penn Libraries call number: GC55 M8899 563s 1570 All images from this book

photo.description: Illustrated bookplate of Harrison Gray Otis. Probably not to be identified with Harrison Gray Otis (1837-1917), publisher of the Los Angeles Times. Possibly to be identified with Harrison Gray Otis (1856-1915), great-grandson of Harrison Gray Otis (1765-1848), U.S. Senator from Massachusetts and Mayor of Boston (and nephew of poet Mercy Otis Warren). His father William Church Otis (1831-1889), a Boston wine merchant and auctioneer, married Margaret Sigourney (b. 1833) in 1855; Harrison Gray Otis was the eldest of their five children. He was a member (though not a graduate) of Harvard's class of 1878 and worked briefly in the wool business before retiring. In a report to a Harvard alumni publication in 1901, he mentions that his time thereafter was devoted to the interests of the Boston Athletic Association. He married Louise MacNamara in 1893 and had 2 sons, William Allyne Otis and Harrison Gray Otis (1895-1901), and a daughter, Marghareta Otis. Lewis J. Bird and Co. of Boston auctioned off at least some of "the private library of Harrison Gray Otis including a ... collection of books printed in the first half century of printing" on 6-7 November 1889 and published a sale catalog, whose LC OCLC record gives "Otis, Harrison Gray, ǂd 1856-1915" as the main entry. (Possibly he was clearing out his father's house? William Church Otis died on 13 March 1889, so the timing is suggestive.) Penn Libraries call number: Inc G-499
photo.title: Illustrated bookplate of Harrison Gray Otis

Text and glosses in brown ink with one large initial "E" in blue and red ink; red capital stroke (and rubric?). Text of left-hand column: Matthew 8:18-19. Text of right-hand column: Matthew 8:28.] Penn Libraries call number: IC55 Za199 C569o

photo.description: "Honora medicam propter necessitatem." (Honor the physician for necessity's sake.) One of 71 woodcut illustrations by Tobias Stimmer from Matthias Holtzwart's Emblematum Tyrocinia, an emblem book printed by Bernhard Jobin in Strasbourg in 1581. For an analysis, see Michael Lailach, "'Der Gelehrten Symbola': Studien zu den Emblematum Tyrocinia von Mathias Holtzwart (Strassburg 1581)," Diss., Eberhard-Karls-Universität Tübingen, 2000. Lailach identifies this woodcut as a depiction of Asclepius and describes it thus: Im Bild des "Emblema.XLVIII." ist ein alter Mann mit einem langen Bart und einer Kappe auf einer Art Thron dargestellt. Er ist von zwei Vögeln, die einen großen Ring und eine Art Ehrenmünze im Schnabel herbeitragen, und von einem Kamel, Esel und Stier umgeben, die mit Schalen und Fässern herantreten. Sie bringen also ehrende Gaben und Geschenke. Zur Rechten des Mannes sind noch ein Hund mit einem Geldbeutel und eine Katze, die auf unübersehbare Weise ihr Geschäft verrichtet, dargestellt. Der Mann schaut auf den Hund und hebt die rechte Hand mit geöffneter Handfläche dem Tier entgegen. Zur Linken des Mannes liegen hingegen ein Wolf und ein Lamm in Eintracht beieinander. (p. 100) Established heading: Stimmer, Tobias, 1539-1584 Established heading: Jobin, Bernhard, d. 1593 Penn Libraries call number: GC55 H7499 581e All images from this book

photo.description: Former coat of arms of the city of Breslau (now Wrocław, Poland), granted to the city by the Holy Roman Emperor Ferdinand I in 1503 and used until 1938. Cf. Wikipedia, which gives the blazon thus: Quarterly, I: Gules, a lion rampant queue fourch erect facing sinister Argent, armed and langued Or outlined Sable, crowned Or outlined Sable; II: Or, an eagle Sable charged with across its breast and wings a crescent Argent upward pointing with a crosslet Argent attached rising from the middle; III: Or, a capital letter 'W' Sable serifed; IV: head and shoulders of St. John the Evangelist gardant Argent, with youthful face and long hair Argent outlined Sable and with halo Or outlined Sable, issuant from an inverted crown Or outlined Sable. Surmounting all at center a roundel Argent, double-bordered in Sable, charged with St. John the Baptist's head Argent, with beard and hair Sable, semi-gardant turned toward the dexter. A somehwat stylized version of these arms is currently (since 1990) used by the city. Penn Libraries call number: GC55 H8997 601d All images from this book
